<section xml:id="Reflection-Rotation">
    <title>Reflection and Rotation</title>
    
<ol>

<li><p>In this figure below, <m>\triangle ABC</m> has reflected over <m>\overleftrightarrow{m}</m> and rotated around <m>D</m> . Do you think we can get from the left triangle to the right triangle in a single rigid motion?</p>
            <example>
            <figure xml:id="reflection_rotation-1">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/reflection_rotation-1.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's reflection and rotation</caption>
           </figure>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>Perhaps you have come to the conclusion that it is a translation and reflection. How would one go about finding the translation and mirror?
</p>
			<example>
            <figure xml:id="reflection_rotation-2">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/reflection_rotation-2.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's related image</caption>
           </figure>
           <hint>
           <p>The most direct way to find the translation is to find the vector between the starting and ending locations of the same point.</p>
           <figure xml:id="reflection_rotation-3">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/reflection_rotation-3.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's single translation</caption>
           </figure>
           </hint>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>Now that we have found the translation vector, how can we find the mirror?</p>
<example>
            <figure xml:id="reflection_rotation-33">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/reflection_rotation-3.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's translation construction</caption>
           </figure>
           
           <hint>
           <p>We can find the mirror by constructing the perpendicular bisector of <m>\overline{A_2A''}</m></p>
           <figure xml:id="reflection_rotation-4">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/reflection_rotation-4.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's reflection construction</caption>
           </figure>
           </hint>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>testing 2 4 6 8 10</p>
